-- 
Emerging Market Stocks Advance on Economic Data, Intel Forecast

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a   a n d   J a s o n   W e b b
-- 
2011-04-20T21:36:14Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-20/emerging-market-stocks-rise-on-u-s-housing-data-intel-forecast.html
Emerging-market stocks rose the
most in 10 months as better-than-forecast U.S. economic data and
earnings from companies including  Intel Corp . and PSA Peugeot
Citroen raised confidence in the global economy.  The MSCI Emerging Markets Index rallied 2.5 percent to
1,194.99, the steepest gain since June. A measure of technology
stocks in the MSCI gauge surged 3.5 percent.  South Korea ’s  Kospi
Index (KOSPI)  jumped 2.2 percent to a record, while  Taiwan ’s Taiex Index
added 2 percent.  India ’s Sensitive Index was up 1.8 percent and
 Brazil ’s Bovespa climbed 1.4 percent. Russia’s Micex Index
advanced 1.6 percent as  oil prices  climbed.  Intel, the biggest chipmaker, forecast second-quarter sales
higher than analysts predicted. Peugeot Citroen,  Europe ’s
second-biggest carmaker, reported first-quarter revenue that
beat estimates. A report from the National Association of
Realtors today showed sales of existing U.S. homes rebounded in
March, a day after Commerce Department figures showed housing
starts rose 7.2 in March compared with February.  “Solid data from the euro-zone and the U.S., as well as
some positive earnings news, have provided strong support” for
emerging-market assets, RBC Capital analysts including  Nigel Rendell  in  London  wrote in a research report.  U.S. home purchases increased 3.7 percent to a 5.1 million
annual rate, exceeding the 5 million median forecast of
economists surveyed by Bloomberg, figures from the National
Association of Realtors showed today in  Washington .  Chipmakers  Hynix Semiconductor Inc. (000660) , the second-largest computer
memory chipmaker, climbed 4.6 percent in  Seoul . Taiwan
Semiconductor Manufacturing Co., the largest contract chipmaker,
rose 2.5 percent.  Korea ’s Samsung Electronics Co. gained 4.7
percent after agreeing to sell its computer hard-disk drive
business.  Intel, the world’s biggest chipmaker, said current quarter
revenue will be $12.8 billion, plus or minus $500 million. That
compares with the $11.9 billion average of analysts’ projections
compiled by Bloomberg.  LG Chem advanced in Seoul, jumping 5.6 percent to its
highest close on record. Net income rose to 656.6 billion won
($607 million) in the three months ended March 31 from 517.7
billion won a year earlier, the company said.  The Bovespa stock index advanced for a second day as
commodities prices climbed. Iron-ore miner  Vale SA (VALE3)  and oil
company Petroleo Brasileiro SA advanced at least 1.7 percent,
following higher metal and crude prices. Cia. Siderurgica
Nacional SA gained 2.5 percent after Rio Tinto Group said in a
statement the Brazilian steelmaker accepted its offer to buy
CSN’s 19.35 percent stake in Riversdale Mining Ltd.  Currencies  The Korean won appreciated 0.8 percent against the dollar
to its strongest level since September 2008. The ruble rose 0.7
percent against the U.S. currency and the rand strengthened 0.7
percent. The Turkish lira gained 0.7 percent.  Crude oil for June delivery jumped as much as 3.3 percent
to $111.60 a barrel in  New York .  Turkey ’s  ISE National 100 Index (XU100)  added 0.5 percent.
Hungary’s BUX Index rallied 1.7 percent and  Poland ’s WIG20
gained 1.3 percent, led by copper producer  KGHM Polska Miedz SA. (KGH)   South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index increased
2.2 percent.  The difference between the yield investors demand from
emerging-market bonds and U.S. Treasuries fell 10 basis points
to 263, according to the JPMorgan Chase EMBI+ Index.  The Markit iTraxx SovX CEEMEA Index of eastern European,
Middle East and Africa credit-default swaps eased four basis
points to 191.  To contact the reporters on this story:
